            <p>May 5 1887<lb/></p>
            <p>Jesse G Burk Esq.<lb/></p>
            <p>My dear Sir<lb/></p>
            <p>Your kind letter was a surprise and a source of<lb/> profound satisfaction to me.  I have been considering whether so<lb/> distinguished an honor as that which the University of Pennsylvania<lb/> purposes to bestow on me is at all deserved.  I do not assume the virtue<lb/> of humility when I say that I have failed to discover any claim to it.<lb/>  Still&#44; I gratefully accept the title to be attached to my name&#44; because I<lb/> imagine that it is designed as a courteous recognition of clerical services<lb/> rendered to the best of my abilities&#44; and because the action of your<lb/> Board may gratify the Congregation to whose spiritual wants I have<lb/> ministered during many years.  God sparing me&#44; I shall be in attendance<lb/> on the day which you will designate.  You may if agreeable allow me a<lb/> few tickets of admission&#45;&#45;no more than six.<lb/></p>
            <p>Thanking your for the language in which your note was couched<lb/> and asking you that you will convey my sentiments of high regard to the<lb/> trustees of the University.<lb/> I remain<lb/> <sic>Yous</sic> very respectfully<lb/></p>
            </body>
    </text>
